sql:
SELECT source_name, source_url
FROM traffic_sources
WHERE is_paid = 1;

SELECT name, domain, purpose
FROM cookies
WHERE cookie_id = 0;

SELECT DISTINCT type_name 
FROM cookie_types 
WHERE is_session_only = 1;

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM users
WHERE is_returning = 1 AND total_visits > (SELECT AVG(total_visits) FROM users);

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT visits.user_id) 
FROM visits 
WHERE visits.domain = 'specific_domain.com';

SELECT DISTINCT c.domain, c.purpose
FROM cookies c
INNER JOIN visit_cookies vc ON c.cookie_id = vc.cookie_id;

external_knowledge:
- "persistent shadow" metaphorically refers to persistent third-party cookies;
- "voyages" metaphorically represent visits (visit_ids);
- "welcomed more than a single persistent shadow" means visits with more than one persistent third-party cookie.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM visits v
WHERE v.domain = 'epfister.pfisterfaucets.com';

SELECT user_id, user_name, total_visits
FROM users
ORDER BY total_visits DESC;

SELECT name, type_name
FROM cookies
WHERE cookie_id > 5;

external_knowledge:
- "seeds" refer to the third-party cookies;
- "strangers" symbolize entities or websites not directly related to the main site (third parties);
- "garden of our digital world" represents the user and cookie database environment.

- The term 'most recent consents' refers to the latest updates where consent is given (True/1).;
- The query filters for consents that are active, indicating user agreement to the cookies' use. The 'cookie details' include the cookie's name, the domain it's associated with, the category it belongs to, and its version. This information helps in understanding what kind of cookies a user is agreeing to use on their visit.;
- 'Users' here refer to individuals who interact with a website or application that uses cookies for various functionalities and data collection. The user's name is used to identify who has given consent.
